1. WHAT IS THE RUNTIME SPECIFICATION
The GIOP Runtime Specification defines the mandatory behavior of any
software component that loads, validates, and applies GIOP formulas,
transforms, and metadata within a live imaging pipeline. It is the
operational contract that guarantees a GIOP-certified tool behaves
identically on any platform, under any load, and in the presence of faults.

2. WHY IT EXISTS
Without a unified runtime specification, independent implementations of
GIOP could diverge in resource scheduling order, fault recovery strategy,
or plugin sandboxing, leading to inconsistent rendering outputs or pipeline
deadlocks. This specification eliminates implementation ambiguity.

3. WHO USES IT
Pipeline TDs, software engineers implementing GIOP-compliant tools, and QA
teams validating runtime behavior across platforms.

4. WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
Any software module that claims GIOP compliance: grading applications,
VFX plugins, media encoders, display calibration firmware, cloud rendering
nodes, and embedded camera firmware.

5. HOW IT IS STRUCTURED
Eight subsystems: Kernel Architecture, Event-Driven Architecture, Plugin
System, Resource Management, Fault Tolerance, Configuration Management,
Observability, and Cross-Platform Compatibility.

6. WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Prevents fragmentation of the GIOP ecosystem. Guarantees that a GIOP
transform produces the same pixel values and the same diagnostic signals
regardless of the operating system or hardware. Provides fault tolerance
rules that stop single component failures from corrupting an entire
multi-layer grade or render.

7. KERNEL ARCHITECTURE

7.1 Design Model
The GIOP runtime kernel SHALL use a hybrid architecture. Core scheduling,
memory mapping, and hash verification run in a monolithic privileged
context for performance. All third-party plugins (custom LMTs, AI inference
engines, codec modules) MUST execute in isolated user-space sandboxes.

7.2 Inter-Process Communication (IPC)
Communication between the core and sandboxed plugins SHALL use message-
passing with a mandatory GIOP IPC protocol. Each message contains a
transaction ID, a plugin ID, a payload (e.g., a frame buffer handle), and
a SHA3-512 integrity hash of the payload. A plugin must acknowledge receipt
within a configurable timeout or the core triggers a fault recovery.

IPC latency, measured from core send to core receive of acknowledgement,
MUST NOT exceed:
  T_ipc = T_syscall + T_msg_copy + T_context_switch + T_scheduler
The runtime SHALL log latency for every transaction and trigger a warning
if any percentile exceeds 5 ms.

7.3 Threading Model
The runtime SHALL be thread-safe. A work-stealing thread pool dispatches
frame-level tasks (IDT, LMT, ODT) across available CPU cores. GPU
operations are dispatched asynchronously to a single graphics queue per
device, respecting Vulkan/Metal/DirectX fence semantics. The runtime
MUST NOT block the UI thread of the host application for more than 16 ms
in any operation, as measured by the host's frame clock.

8. EVENT-DRIVEN ARCHITECTURE

8.1 Event Bus
All internal state changes and external notifications SHALL be communicated
through a publish-subscribe event bus. Events are typed and versioned.

8.2 Event Schema
Every event MUST contain:
  event_id: UUID v4
  event_type: string (registered in GIOP event registry)
  timestamp: TAI nanoseconds since epoch
  producer_id: runtime instance UUID
  payload: JSON or binary blob, schema-registered
  severity: INFO, WARNING, ERROR, FATAL

8.3 Mandatory Events
The runtime SHALL emit these events:
  - giop.frame.processed (payload: frame number, pipeline stage, timing)
  - giop.plugin.loaded (plugin ID, hash, certification level)
  - giop.fault.detected (fault type, affected component, recovery action)
  - giop.config.changed (changed key, previous value, new value)
  - giop.shutdown (reason, pending tasks count)

8.4 Event Throughput and Latency
The event bus MUST sustain a throughput of at least 100,000 events per
second without dropping events. End-to-end latency from event production
to last subscriber delivery MUST be logged and SHALL not exceed 1 ms for
INFO severity events on the local machine.

9. PLUGIN SYSTEM

9.1 Isolation Strategies
Plugins MUST be isolated using one of the following methods, selectable
by the runtime administrator:
  - Process isolation: plugin runs as a separate OS process, IPC via
    shared memory. Maximum overhead tolerated: 0.5 ms per frame.
  - Container isolation: plugin runs in a sandboxed container (e.g., Docker,
    gVisor) on the same host. Overhead must be profiled per plugin.
  - Thread isolation: plugin runs in the same process but in a dedicated
    thread with restricted syscalls (seccomp on Linux, sandbox on macOS).
  - WASM sandbox: plugin is compiled to WebAssembly and executed in a
    WASI-compliant runtime. This is mandatory for all JavaScript/Python-
    based plugins distributed via the GIOP marketplace.

9.2 Plugin Manifest
Each plugin SHALL include a digitally signed manifest containing:
  - plugin_id (reverse-DNS, e.g., com.giop.plugin.lmt.film_look)
  - version (SemVer)
  - certified_level (A, B, or C)
  - target_giop_runtime (minimum version)
  - isolation_preference (ordered list from above)
  - resource_requirements (max GPU memory, CPU cores, bandwidth)
  - hash of the plugin binary (SHA3-512)

9.3 Plugin Load and Verification
Before a plugin is loaded, the runtime SHALL:
  - Verify the manifest signature against the GIOP-F public key.
  - Compute the hash of the loaded binary and compare against the manifest.
  - If mismatch, block loading and emit a giop.fault.detected event with
    severity ERROR.
  - After successful load, measure T_load = T_read + T_parse + T_verify + T_init
    and log it. If T_load exceeds 5 seconds, the runtime SHOULD alert the user.

9.4 Mandatory Plugin API
Every plugin MUST implement three functions:
  - init(config): called once on load; returns error code.
  - process(frame_buffer, metadata): called per frame; returns processed
    buffer and an output metadata block; must be reentrant.
  - destroy(): called on unload; frees all resources.
All frame buffers SHALL be 16-bit half-float or 32-bit float, in ACEScg
linear encoding unless the plugin declares otherwise in its manifest.

10. RESOURCE MANAGEMENT

10.1 GPU Memory Estimation
Before processing a frame, the runtime SHALL estimate peak GPU memory M_peak:
  M_peak = M_model + M_activations + M_gradients + M_optimizer
where M_model is the static weight memory for any neural plugins,
M_activations is the maximum intermediate buffer size, M_gradients is
non-zero only during training, and M_optimizer is optimizer state memory.
The runtime MUST compare M_peak against available GPU memory and refuse
to start a new operation if insufficient headroom remains (minimum 10% free).

10.2 Power and Thermal Budgeting
On battery-powered devices, the runtime SHALL compute power consumption:
  P_total = P_dynamic + P_static
where P_dynamic = C * V^2 * f (C is effective capacitance, V voltage,
f frequency). The runtime MUST throttle internal thread pool frequency
when remaining battery capacity drops below 20%, targeting a discharge
rate that ensures safe completion of the current job queue.
  T_battery = Capacity_mAh / (I_idle + I_active * U_cpu + I_gpu * U_gpu + I_radio * U_radio)
where U_ are utilization factors. The runtime SHALL estimate T_battery and
emit a warning if estimated duration is less than the active project length.

10.3 Scheduling
Frame tasks are scheduled based on priority classes:
  - REALTIME: for live grading and virtual production (deadline < 16 ms).
  - INTERACTIVE: for GUI preview renders (deadline < 100 ms).
  - BATCH: for offline export and encoding (deadline configurable).
The scheduler MUST preempt BATCH tasks when REALTIME tasks arrive,
context-switching within 2 ms.

11. FAULT TOLERANCE

11.1 Circuit Breaker Model
All external service calls (cloud rendering, license verification) SHALL
go through a circuit breaker with states:
  - CLOSED: normal operation. Failure rate F = Failures / (Successes + Failures)
    tracked over a sliding window of 60 seconds.
  - OPEN: when F exceeds a threshold (default 0.5 for 10 consecutive calls),
    the breaker opens, immediately failing all calls for a cool-down period
    (default 30 seconds).
  - HALF-OPEN: after cool-down, a single trial call is permitted. If it
    succeeds, the breaker closes. If it fails, the breaker returns to OPEN.

11.2 Fault Detection
The runtime SHALL inspect every output frame buffer for:
  - NaN or Inf values in any pixel channel; if detected, mark the frame as
    corrupted and replace with the previous valid frame (or a solid magenta
    warning frame) while logging the fault.
  - Luminance values exceeding 10,000 cd/m^2 for PQ output or the mastering
    display peak for other EOTFs; if exceeded, the runtime SHALL hard-clip
    and emit a warning event.
  - Sensor fault flags embedded in RAW metadata (dead pixel map, black
    level instability). If any flag is set, the runtime SHALL engage the
    corresponding correction algorithm and log the event.

11.3 Recovery
When a plugin process crashes or times out, the runtime SHALL:
  - Isolate the plugin's allocated resources and free them.
  - Restart the plugin with exponential backoff: delay = base_delay * 2^attempt
    + random_jitter, where base_delay = 1 second, max attempts = 3.
  - If the plugin fails 3 consecutive times, the runtime SHALL route all
    further frames through a bypass path (identity transform) and emit a
    FATAL event.

11.4 Bulkhead Pattern
Resource pools (thread pools, GPU memory pools) are partitioned by
function: IDT/LMT processing, ODT processing, display encoding, and
UI rendering. Exhaustion of one pool MUST NOT cause starvation of another.
The runtime SHALL reserve a minimum number of threads (2) for UI rendering
at all times.

12. CONFIGURATION MANAGEMENT

12.1 Configuration Sources
The runtime SHALL load configuration with the following priority (highest
first):
  1. Command-line flags
  2. Environment variables
  3. Configuration files (YAML, JSON, or TOML; YAML is recommended)
  4. Factory defaults

12.2 Schema
All configuration keys SHALL be namespaced (e.g., giop.runtime.threads,
giop.gpu.device). A mandatory JSON schema is provided by GIOP-F and the
runtime MUST validate loaded config against it at startup. Invalid config
triggers immediate shutdown with a FATAL event.

12.3 Feature Flags
Feature flags SHALL use a consistent pattern: giop.feature.<name>.enabled.
The runtime supports boolean flags, percentage rollouts (0-100), and
targeted flags (by user or machine ID). Flags are reloadable within 5
seconds without restart.

12.4 Immutable Config Audit Trail
Every configuration change SHALL be logged with timestamp, source, old
value, and new value. The hash of the active configuration file (SHA3-512)
SHALL be included in the metadata of every rendered frame, ensuring full
reproducibility.

13. OBSERVABILITY

13.1 The Three Pillars
Metrics: exported in Prometheus-compatible format on port 9101 by default.
Logs: structured JSON logs to stdout and optionally to a remote collector.
Traces: OpenTelemetry spans for every pipeline stage, with W3C trace context
propagated across IPC calls.

13.2 Mandatory Metrics
  - giop_frame_processing_duration_seconds (histogram, per stage)
  - giop_pipeline_errors_total (counter, per error type)
  - giop_gpu_memory_used_bytes (gauge)
  - giop_active_plugins (gauge)
  - giop_event_bus_latency_seconds (histogram)
  - giop_plugin_load_time_seconds (histogram)

13.3 RED and USE Methods
RED for the plugin API (Rate of calls, Errors, Duration of process()).
USE for resources (Utilization of GPU, Saturation of thread pool, Errors
from memory allocation).

13.4 Alerts
Alert rules SHALL be defined for:
  - Frame processing latency exceeding 90th percentile threshold > 100 ms
    for REALTIME tasks.
  - Circuit breaker OPEN state lasting > 5 minutes.
  - GPU memory utilization exceeding 85% for more than 2 minutes.

14. CROSS-PLATFORM COMPATIBILITY

14.1 Supported Platforms
The GIOP runtime MUST compile and run on:
  - Windows 10/11 (x86-64)
  - macOS 14+ (Apple Silicon and x86-64)
  - Linux (kernel 5.15+, glibc 2.35+)
  - iOS 18+ (as a static library)
  - Android 15+ (as a shared library with NDK)
  - WebAssembly (for browser-based validation, limited feature set)

14.2 Graphics API Abstraction
GPU code SHALL be written against a GIOP abstraction layer that maps to
Vulkan 1.3, Metal 3, and DirectX 12 Ultimate. The runtime selects the
backend at startup. All shaders are pre-compiled to SPIR-V and Metal IR
and distributed with the runtime; no runtime shader compilation is permitted
on end-user machines.

14.3 Numerical Consistency
Floating-point operations SHALL conform to IEEE 754. For deterministic
rendering across platforms, the runtime SHALL use a single portable math
library (e.g., SLEEF) for transcendental functions and SHALL NOT rely on
fast-math compiler flags. Any deviation from reference output exceeding
1e-6 relative error on a standard test vector SHALL be reported as a bug.

14.4 File Paths and Encodings
All paths SHALL use POSIX-style forward slashes internally and are converted
at the platform abstraction layer. Text files SHALL be UTF-8 without BOM.
Line endings SHALL be LF internally, with automatic conversion on I/O for
Windows consumers.

